# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: photochemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescence occurs when a photon from incoming radiation is absorbed by a molecule, exciting it to a higher energy level, followed by the emission of light as the molecule returns to a lower energy state.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The emitted light may have a longer wavelength and, therefore, a lower photon energy than the absorbed radiation.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] For example, the absorbed radiation could be in the ultraviolet region of the electromagnetic spectrum (invisible to the human eye), while the emitted light is in the visible region.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] This gives the fluorescent substance a distinct color, best seen when exposed to UV light, making it appear to glow in the dark.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] However, any light with a shorter wavelength may cause a material to fluoresce at a longer wavelength.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescent materials may also be excited by certain wavelengths of visible light, which can mask the glow, yet their colors may appear bright and intensified.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Other fluorescent materials emit their light in the infrared or even the ultraviolet regions of the spectrum.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescence has many practical applications, including mineralogy, gemology, medicine, chemical sensors (fluorescence spectroscopy), fluorescent labelling, dyes, biological detectors, cosmic-ray detection, vacuum fluorescent displays, and cathode-ray tubes.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Its most common everyday application is in (gas-discharge) fluorescent lamps and LED lamps, where fluorescent coatings convert UV or blue light into longer wavelengths, resulting in white light, which can appear indistinguishable from that of the traditional but energy-inefficient incandescent lamp.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescence also occurs frequently in nature, appearing in some minerals and many biological forms across all kingdoms of life.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The latter is often referred to as *biofluorescence*, indicating that the fluorophore is part of or derived from a living organism (rather than an inorganic dye or stain).
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] However, since fluorescence results from a specific chemical property that can often be synthesized artificially, it is generally sufficient to describe the substance itself as *fluorescent*.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescence was observed long before it was named and understood.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] An early observation of fluorescence was known to the Aztecs and described in 1560 by Bernardino de Sahagún and in 1565 by Nicolás Monardes in the infusion known as *lignum nephriticum* (Latin for "kidney wood").
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] It was derived from the wood of two tree species, *Pterocarpus indicus* and *Eysenhardtia polystachya*.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The chemical compound responsible for this fluorescence is matlaline, which is the oxidation product of one of the flavonoids found in this wood.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Clarke and in 1822 René Just Haüy described some varieties of fluorites that had a different color depending on whether the light was reflected or (apparently) transmitted.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Haüy incorrectly viewed the effect as light scattering similar to opalescence.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] In 1833 Sir David Brewster described a similar effect in chlorophyll which he also considered a form of opalescence.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Sir John Herschel studied quinine in 1845 and came to a different incorrect conclusion.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Becquerel observed that calcium sulfide emits light after being exposed to solar ultraviolet, making him the first to state that the emitted light is of longer wavelength than the incident light.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] While his observation of photoluminescence was similar to that described 10 years later by Stokes, who observed a fluorescence of a solution of quinine, the phenomenon that Becquerel described with calcium sulfide is now called phosphorescence.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] In his 1852 paper on the "Refrangibility" (wavelength change) of light, George Gabriel Stokes described the ability of fluorspar, uranium glass and many other substances to change invisible light beyond the violet end of the visible spectrum into visible light.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Neither Becquerel nor Stokes understood one key aspect of photoluminescence: the critical difference from incandescence, the emission of light by heated material.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] To distinguish it from incandescence, in the late 1800s, Gustav Wiedemann proposed the term luminescence to designate any emission of light more intense than expected from the source's temperature.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Advances in spectroscopy and quantum electronics between the 1950s and 1970s provided a way to distinguish between the three different mechanisms that produce the light, as well as narrowing down the typical timescales those mechanisms take to decay after absorption.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] In modern science, this distinction became important because some items, such as lasers, required the fastest decay times, which typically occur in the nanosecond (billionth of a second) range.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] In physics, this first mechanism was termed "fluorescence" or "singlet emission", and is common in many laser mediums such as ruby.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The typical decay times ranged from a few microseconds to one second, which are still fast enough by human-eye standards to be colloquially referred to as fluorescent.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Common examples include fluorescent lamps, organic dyes, and even fluorspar.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Longer emitters, commonly referred to as glow-in-the-dark substances, ranged from one second to many hours, and this mechanism was called persistent phosphorescence or persistent luminescence, to distinguish it from the other two mechanisms.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] When an excited molecule, atom, or nanostructure, emits a photon and the lower energy state (usually the ground state) has the same electronic spin multiplicity as the excited state, the process is called *fluorescence*.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] When the initial and final states have different multiplicity (spin), the phenomenon is termed *phosphorescence*.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] When a molecule in its ground state (called S0) is photoexcited it may end up in any one of a number of excited electronic states (S1, S2, S3,...).
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] It can occupy different vibrational states within the electronic state.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] These vibrational states are populated in proportion to their overlap with the ground state according to the Franck-Condon principle.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] These vibrational excited states typically decay rapidly to the ground vibrational state of the excited electronic state S1, followed by radiative transition to the ground state or to vibrational states close to the ground state.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] A different pathway for deexcitation is intersystem crossing from the S1 to a triplet state T1.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Decay from T1 to S0 is typically slower and less intense and is called phosphorescence.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Absorption of a photon of energy $h\nu _{ex}$ results in an excited state of the same multiplicity (spin) of the ground state, usually a singlet (Sn with n > 0).
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] In solution, states with n > 1 relax rapidly to the lowest vibrational level of the first excited state (S1) by transferring energy to the solvent molecules through non-radiative processes, including internal conversion followed by vibrational relaxation, in which the energy is dissipated as heat.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Thus the fluorescence energy is typically less than the photoexcitation energy.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The excited state S1 can relax by other mechanisms that do not involve the emission of light.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] These processes, called non-radiative processes, compete with fluorescence emission and decrease its efficiency.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Examples include internal conversion, intersystem crossing to the triplet state, and energy transfer to another molecule.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] An example of energy transfer is Förster resonance energy transfer.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Relaxation from an excited state can also occur through collisional quenching, a process where a molecule (the quencher) collides with the fluorescent molecule during its excited state lifetime.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Molecular oxygen (O2) is an extremely efficient quencher of fluorescence because of its unusual triplet ground state.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The fluorescence quantum yield gives the efficiency of the fluorescence process.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] It is defined as the ratio of the number of photons emitted to the number of photons absorbed.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The maximum possible fluorescence quantum yield is 1.0 (100%); each photon absorbed results in a photon emitted.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Compounds with quantum yields of 0.10 are still considered quite fluorescent.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] is the sum of all rates of excited state decay.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Thus, if the rate of any pathway changes, both the excited state lifetime and the fluorescence quantum yield will be affected.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescence quantum yields are measured by comparison to a standard.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The quinine salt *quinine sulfate* in a sulfuric acid solution was regarded as the most common fluorescence standard, however, a recent study revealed that the fluorescence quantum yield of this solution is strongly affected by the temperature, and should no longer be used as the standard solution.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The quinine in 0.1 M perchloric acid (Φ = 0.60) shows no temperature dependence up to 45 °C, therefore it can be considered as a reliable standard solution.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The fluorescence lifetime refers to the average time the molecule stays in its excited state before emitting a photon.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] where $\left[S_{1}\right]$ is the concentration of excited state molecules at time t , $\left[S_{1}\right]_{0}$ is the initial concentration and $\Gamma$ is the decay rate or the inverse of the fluorescence lifetime.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] This is an instance of exponential decay.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Various radiative and non-radiative processes can de-populate the excited state.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] where $\Gamma _{tot}$ is the total decay rate, $\Gamma _{rad}$ the radiative decay rate and $\Gamma _{nrad}$ the non-radiative decay rate.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] It is similar to a first-order chemical reaction in which the first-order rate constant is the sum of all of the rates (a parallel kinetic model).
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] If the rate of spontaneous emission, or any of the other rates are fast, the lifetime is short.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] For commonly used fluorescent compounds, typical excited state decay times for photon emissions with energies from the UV to near infrared are within the range of 0.5 to 20 nanoseconds.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The fluorescence lifetime is an important parameter for practical applications of fluorescence such as fluorescence resonance energy transfer and fluorescence-lifetime imaging microscopy.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The Jablonski diagram describes most of the relaxation mechanisms for excited state molecules.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The diagram alongside shows how fluorescence occurs due to the relaxation of certain excited electrons of a molecule.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorophores are more likely to be excited by photons if the transition moment of the fluorophore is parallel to the electric vector of the photon.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The polarization of the emitted light will also depend on the transition moment.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The transition moment is dependent on the physical orientation of the fluorophore molecule.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] For fluorophores in solution, the intensity and polarization of the emitted light is dependent on rotational diffusion.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Therefore, anisotropy measurements can be used to investigate how freely a fluorescent molecule moves in a particular environment.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] where $I_{\parallel }$ is the emitted intensity parallel to the polarization of the excitation light and $I_{\perp }$ is the emitted intensity perpendicular to the polarization of the excitation light.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Anisotropy is independent of the intensity of the absorbed or emitted light, it is the property of the light, so photobleaching of the dye will not affect the anisotropy value as long as the signal is detectable.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Strongly fluorescent pigments often have an unusual appearance which is often described colloquially as a "neon color" (originally "day-glo" in the late 1960s, early 1970s).
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] This phenomenon was termed "Farbenglut" by Hermann von Helmholtz and "fluorence" by Ralph M.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] It is generally thought to be related to the high brightness of the color relative to what it would be as a component of white.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescence shifts energy in the incident illumination from shorter wavelengths to longer (such as blue to yellow) and thus can make the fluorescent color appear brighter (more saturated) than it could possibly be by reflection alone.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] There are several general rules that deal with fluorescence.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Each of the following rules have exceptions but they are useful guidelines for understanding fluorescence (these rules do not necessarily apply to two-photon absorption).
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Kasha's rule states that the luminesce (fluorescence or phosphorescence) of a molecule will be emitted only from the lowest excited state of its given multiplicity.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Vavilov's rule (a logical extension of Kasha's rule thusly called Kasha–Vavilov rule) dictates that the quantum yield of luminescence is independent of the wavelength of exciting radiation and is proportional to the absorbance of the excited wavelength.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Kasha's rule does not always apply and is violated by simple molecules, such an example is azulene.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] A somewhat more reliable statement, although still with exceptions, would be that the fluorescence spectrum shows very little dependence on the wavelength of exciting radiation.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] For many fluorophores the absorption spectrum is a mirror image of the emission spectrum.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] This is known as the mirror image rule and is related to the Franck–Condon principle which states that electronic transitions are vertical, that is energy changes without distance changing as can be represented with a vertical line in Jablonski diagram.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] This means the nucleus does not move and the vibration levels of the excited state resemble the vibration levels of the ground state.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] In general, emitted fluorescence light has a longer wavelength and lower energy than the absorbed light.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] This phenomenon, known as Stokes shift, is due to energy loss between the time a photon is absorbed and when a new one is emitted.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The causes and magnitude of Stokes shift can be complex and are dependent on the fluorophore and its environment.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] It is frequently due to non-radiative decay to the lowest vibrational energy level of the excited state.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Another factor is that the emission of fluorescence frequently leaves a fluorophore in a higher vibrational level of the ground state.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] There are many natural compounds that exhibit fluorescence, and they have a number of applications.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Some deep-sea animals, such as the greeneye, have fluorescent structures.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescence is the phenomenon of absorption of electromagnetic radiation, typically from ultraviolet or visible light, by a molecule and the subsequent emission of a photon of a lower energy (smaller frequency, longer wavelength).
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] This causes the light that is emitted to be a different color from the light that is absorbed.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Stimulating light excites an electron to an excited state.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] When the molecule returns to the ground state, it releases a photon, which is the fluorescent emission.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The excited state lifetime is short, so emission of light is typically only observable when the absorbing light is on.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescence can be of any wavelength but is often more significant when emitted photons are in the visible spectrum.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] When it occurs in a living organism, it is sometimes called biofluorescence.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescence should not be confused with bioluminescence and biophosphorescence.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Pumpkin toadlets that live in the Brazilian Atlantic forest are fluorescent.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Bioluminescence differs from fluorescence in that it is the natural production of light by chemical reactions within an organism, whereas fluorescence is the absorption and reemission of light from the environment.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fireflies and anglerfish are two examples of bioluminescent organisms.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] To add to the potential confusion, some organisms are both bioluminescent and fluorescent, like the sea pansy Renilla reniformis, where bioluminescence serves as the light source for fluorescence.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Phosphorescence is similar to fluorescence in its requirement of light wavelengths as a provider of excitation energy.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The difference here lies in the relative stability of the energized electron.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Unlike with fluorescence, in phosphorescence the electron retains stability, emitting light that continues to "glow in the dark" even after the stimulating light source has been removed.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] For example, glow-in-the-dark stickers are phosphorescent, but there are no truly *biophosphorescent* animals known.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Pigment cells that exhibit fluorescence are called fluorescent chromatophores, and function somatically similar to regular chromatophores.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] These cells are dendritic, and contain pigments called fluorosomes.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] These pigments contain fluorescent proteins which are activated by K+ (potassium) ions, and it is their movement, aggregation, and dispersion within the fluorescent chromatophore that cause directed fluorescence patterning.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescent cells are innervated the same as other chromatophores, like melanophores, pigment cells that contain melanin.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Short term fluorescent patterning and signaling is controlled by the nervous system.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescent chromatophores can be found in the skin (e.g. in fish) just below the epidermis, amongst other chromatophores.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Epidermal fluorescent cells in fish also respond to hormonal stimuli by the α–MSH and MCH hormones much the same as melanophores.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] This suggests that fluorescent cells may have color changes throughout the day that coincide with their circadian rhythm.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fish may also be sensitive to cortisol induced stress responses to environmental stimuli, such as interaction with a predator or engaging in a mating ritual.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The incidence of fluorescence across the tree of life is widespread, and has been studied most extensively in cnidarians and fish.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The phenomenon appears to have evolved multiple times in multiple taxa such as in the anguilliformes (eels), gobioidei (gobies and cardinalfishes), and tetradontiformes (triggerfishes), along with the other taxa discussed later in the article.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescence is highly genotypically and phenotypically variable even within ecosystems, in regards to the wavelengths emitted, the patterns displayed, and the intensity of the fluorescence.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Generally, the species relying upon camouflage exhibit the greatest diversity in fluorescence, likely because camouflage may be one of the uses of fluorescence.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] It is suspected by some scientists that GFPs and GFP-like proteins began as electron donors activated by light.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] These electrons were then used for reactions requiring light energy.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Functions of fluorescent proteins, such as protection from the sun, conversion of light into different wavelengths, or for signaling are thought to have evolved secondarily.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Currently, relatively little is known about the functional significance of fluorescence and fluorescent proteins.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] However, it is suspected that fluorescence may serve important functions in signaling and communication, mating, lures, camouflage, UV protection and antioxidation, photoacclimation, dinoflagellate regulation, and in coral health.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Water absorbs light of long wavelengths, so less light from these wavelengths reflects back to reach the eye.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Therefore, warm colors from the visual light spectrum appear less vibrant at increasing depths.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Water scatters light of shorter wavelengths above violet, meaning cooler colors dominate the visual field in the photic zone.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Light intensity decreases 10 fold with every 75 m of depth, so at depths of 75 m, light is 10% as intense as it is on the surface, and is only 1% as intense at 150 m as it is on the surface.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Because the water filters out the wavelengths and intensity of water reaching certain depths, different proteins, because of the wavelengths and intensities of light they are capable of absorbing, are better suited to different depths.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Theoretically, some fish eyes can detect light as deep as 1000 m.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] At these depths of the aphotic zone, the only sources of light are organisms themselves, giving off light through chemical reactions in a process called bioluminescence.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescence is simply defined as the absorption of electromagnetic radiation at one wavelength and its reemission at another, lower energy wavelength.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Thus any type of fluorescence depends on the presence of external sources of light.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Biologically functional fluorescence is found in the photic zone, where there is not only enough light to cause fluorescence, but enough light for other organisms to detect it.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The visual field in the photic zone is naturally blue, so colors of fluorescence can be detected as bright reds, oranges, yellows, and greens.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Green is the most commonly found color in the marine spectrum, yellow the second most, orange the third, and red is the rarest.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescence can occur in organisms in the aphotic zone as a byproduct of that same organism's bioluminescence.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Some fluorescence in the aphotic zone is merely a byproduct of the organism's tissue biochemistry and does not have a functional purpose.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] However, some cases of functional and adaptive significance of fluorescence in the aphotic zone of the deep ocean is an active area of research.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Bony fishes living in shallow water generally have good color vision due to their living in a colorful environment.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Thus, in shallow-water fishes, red, orange, and green fluorescence most likely serves as a means of communication with conspecifics, especially given the great phenotypic variance of the phenomenon.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Many fish that exhibit fluorescence, such as sharks, lizardfish, scorpionfish, wrasses, and flatfishes, also possess yellow intraocular filters.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Yellow intraocular filters in the lenses and cornea of certain fishes function as long-pass filters.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] These filters enable the species to visualize and potentially exploit fluorescence, in order to enhance visual contrast and patterns that are unseen to other fishes and predators that lack this visual specialization.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fish that possess the necessary yellow intraocular filters for visualizing fluorescence potentially exploit a light signal from members of it.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescent patterning was especially prominent in cryptically patterned fishes possessing complex camouflage.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Many of these lineages also possess yellow long-pass intraocular filters that could enable visualization of such patterns.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Another adaptive use of fluorescence is to generate orange and red light from the ambient blue light of the photic zone to aid vision.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Red light can only be seen across short distances due to attenuation of red light wavelengths by water.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Many fish species that fluoresce are small, group-living, or benthic/aphotic, and have conspicuous patterning.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] This patterning is caused by fluorescent tissue and is visible to other members of the species, however the patterning is invisible at other visual spectra.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] These intraspecific fluorescent patterns also coincide with intra-species signaling.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The patterns present in ocular rings to indicate directionality of an individual's gaze, and along fins to indicate directionality of an individual's movement.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Current research suspects that this red fluorescence is used for private communication between members of the same species.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Due to the prominence of blue light at ocean depths, red light and light of longer wavelengths are muddled, and many predatory reef fish have little to no sensitivity for light at these wavelengths.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Thus, fluorescence can be used as adaptive signaling and intra-species communication in reef fish.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Additionally, it is suggested that fluorescent tissues that surround an organism's eyes are used to convert blue light from the photic zone or green bioluminescence in the aphotic zone into red light to aid vision.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] A new fluorophore was described in two species of sharks, wherein it was due to an undescribed group of brominated tryptophane-kynurenine small molecule metabolites.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescence serves a wide variety of functions in coral.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescent proteins in corals may contribute to photosynthesis by converting otherwise unusable wavelengths of light into ones for which the coral's symbiotic algae are able to conduct photosynthesis.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Also, the proteins may fluctuate in number as more or less light becomes available as a means of photoacclimation.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Similarly, these fluorescent proteins may possess antioxidant capacities to eliminate oxygen radicals produced by photosynthesis.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Finally, through modulating photosynthesis, the fluorescent proteins may also serve as a means of regulating the activity of the coral's photosynthetic algal symbionts.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Another, well-studied example of fluorescence in the ocean is the hydrozoan *Aequorea victoria*.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] This jellyfish lives in the photic zone off the west coast of North America and was identified as a carrier of green fluorescent protein (GFP) by Osamu Shimomura.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The gene for these green fluorescent proteins has been isolated and is scientifically significant because it is widely used in genetic studies to indicate the expression of other genes.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Several species of mantis shrimp, which are stomatopod crustaceans, including *Lysiosquillina glabriuscula*, have yellow fluorescent markings along their antennal scales and carapace (shell) that males present during threat displays to predators and other males.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The display involves raising the head and thorax, spreading the striking appendages and other maxillipeds, and extending the prominent, oval antennal scales laterally, which makes the animal appear larger and accentuates its yellow fluorescent markings.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Furthermore, as depth increases, mantis shrimp fluorescence accounts for a greater part of the visible light available.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] During mating rituals, mantis shrimp actively fluoresce, and the wavelength of this fluorescence matches the wavelengths detected by their eye pigments.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The predatory deep-sea dragonfish *Malacosteus niger*, the closely related genus *Aristostomias* and the species *Pachystomias microdon* use fluorescent red accessory pigments to convert the blue light emitted from their own bioluminescence to red light from suborbital photophores.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] This red luminescence is invisible to other animals, which allows these dragonfish extra light at dark ocean depths without attracting or signaling predators.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescence is widespread among amphibians and has been documented in several families of frogs, salamanders and caecilians, but the extent of it varies greatly.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The polka-dot tree frog (*Hypsiboas punctatus*), widely found in South America, was unintentionally discovered to be the first fluorescent amphibian in 2017.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The fluorescence was traced to a new compound found in the lymph and skin glands.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The main fluorescent compound is Hyloin-L1 and it gives a blue-green glow when exposed to violet or ultraviolet light.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The scientists behind the discovery suggested that the fluorescence can be used for communication.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] They speculated that fluorescence possibly is relatively widespread among frogs.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Only a few months later, fluorescence was discovered in the closely related *Hypsiboas atlanticus*.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Because it is linked to secretions from skin glands, they can also leave fluorescent markings on surfaces where they have been.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] In 2019, two other frogs, the tiny pumpkin toadlet (*Brachycephalus ephippium*) and red pumpkin toadlet (*B. pitanga*) of southeastern Brazil, were found to have naturally fluorescent skeletons, which are visible through their skin when exposed to ultraviolet light.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] In 2020 it was confirmed that green or yellow fluorescence is widespread not only in adult frogs that are exposed to blue or ultraviolet light, but also among tadpoles, salamanders and caecilians.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The extent varies greatly depending on species; in some it is highly distinct and in others it is barely noticeable.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] It can be based on their skin pigmentation, their mucus or their bones.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Swallowtail (*Papilio*) butterflies have complex systems for emitting fluorescent light.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Their wings contain pigment-infused crystals that provide directed fluorescent light.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] These crystals function to produce fluorescent light best when they absorb radiance from sky-blue light (wavelength about 420 nm).
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The wavelengths of light that the butterflies see the best correspond to the absorbance of the crystals in the butterfly's wings.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] This likely functions to enhance the capacity for signaling.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Parrots have fluorescent plumage that may be used in mate signaling.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] A study using mate-choice experiments on budgerigars (*Melopsittacus undulates*) found compelling support for fluorescent sexual signaling, with both males and females significantly preferring birds with the fluorescent experimental stimulus.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] This study suggests that the fluorescent plumage of parrots is not simply a by-product of pigmentation, but instead an adapted sexual signal.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Considering the intricacies of the pathways that produce fluorescent pigments, there may be significant costs involved.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Therefore, individuals exhibiting strong fluorescence may be honest indicators of high individual quality, since they can deal with the associated costs.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Spiders fluoresce under UV light and possess a huge diversity of fluorophores.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Andrews, Reed, & Masta noted that spiders are the only known group in which fluorescence is "taxonomically widespread, variably expressed, evolutionarily labile, and probably under selection and potentially of ecological importance for intraspecific and interspecific signaling".
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] They showed that fluorescence evolved multiple times across spider taxa, with novel fluorophores evolving during spider diversification.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] In some spiders, ultraviolet cues are important for predator–prey interactions, intraspecific communication, and camouflage-matching with fluorescent flowers.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Differing ecological contexts could favor inhibition or enhancement of fluorescence expression, depending upon whether fluorescence helps spiders be cryptic or makes them more conspicuous to predators.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Therefore, natural selection could be acting on expression of fluorescence across spider species.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Scorpions are also fluorescent, in their case due to the presence of beta-carboline in their cuticles.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] In 2020 fluorescence was reported for several platypus specimens.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] In 2019 it was observed, by chance, that a flying squirrel fluoresced pink under UV light.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Subsequent research by biologists at Northland College in Northern Wisconsin found that this is true for all three species of North American flying squirrels.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Non-flying squirrels do not fluoresce under UV light.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] This fluorescence may be an accident of evolution and serve no biological purpose.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Many plants are fluorescent due to the presence of chlorophyll, which is probably the most widely distributed fluorescent molecule, producing red emission under a range of excitation wavelengths.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] This attribute of chlorophyll is commonly used by ecologists to measure photosynthetic efficiency.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The *Mirabilis jalapa* flower contains violet, fluorescent betacyanins and yellow, fluorescent betaxanthins.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Under white light, parts of the flower containing only betaxanthins appear yellow, but in areas where both betaxanthins and betacyanins are present, the visible fluorescence of the flower is faded due to internal light-filtering mechanisms.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescence was previously suggested to play a role in pollinator attraction, however, it was later found that the visual signal by fluorescence is negligible compared to the visual signal of light reflected by the flower.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] A rare hybrid within *Nepenthes* (*N. benstonei* x *N. rafflesiana*) which was discovered in 2025 was reported to exhibit vivid green fluorescence on the peristomes of matured pitchers, while more juvenile pitchers exhibited blue fluorescence.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Prior to this report, only blue fluorescence had been reported in the genus.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] In addition to the eponymous fluorspar, many gemstones and minerals may have a distinctive fluorescence or may fluoresce differently under short-wave ultraviolet, long-wave ultraviolet, visible light, or X-rays.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Many types of calcite and amber will fluoresce under shortwave UV, longwave UV and visible light.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Rubies, emeralds, and diamonds exhibit red fluorescence under long-wave UV, blue and sometimes green light; diamonds also emit light under X-ray radiation.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescence in minerals is caused by a wide range of activators.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] In some cases, the concentration of the activator must be restricted to below a certain level, to prevent quenching of the fluorescent emission.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Furthermore, the mineral must be free of impurities such as iron or copper, to prevent quenching of possible fluorescence.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Divalent manganese, in concentrations of up to several percent, is responsible for the red or orange fluorescence of calcite, the green fluorescence of willemite, the yellow fluorescence of esperite, and the orange fluorescence of wollastonite and clinohedrite.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Trivalent chromium at low concentration is the source of the red fluorescence of ruby.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Divalent europium is the source of the blue fluorescence, when seen in the mineral fluorite.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Trivalent lanthanides such as terbium and dysprosium are the principal activators of the creamy yellow fluorescence exhibited by the yttrofluorite variety of the mineral fluorite, and contribute to the orange fluorescence of zircon.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Powellite (calcium molybdate) and scheelite (calcium tungstate) fluoresce intrinsically in yellow and blue, respectively.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] When present together in solid solution, energy is transferred from the higher-energy tungsten to the lower-energy molybdenum, such that fairly low levels of molybdenum are sufficient to cause a yellow emission for scheelite, instead of blue.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Low-iron sphalerite (zinc sulfide), fluoresces and phosphoresces in a range of colors, influenced by the presence of various trace impurities.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Crude oil (petroleum) fluoresces in a range of colors, from dull-brown for heavy oils and tars through to bright-yellowish and bluish-white for very light oils and condensates.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] This phenomenon is used in oil exploration drilling to identify very small amounts of oil in drill cuttings and core samples.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Humic acids and fulvic acids produced by the degradation of organic matter in soils (humus) may also fluoresce because of the presence of aromatic cycles in their complex molecular structures.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Humic substances dissolved in groundwater can be detected and characterized by spectrofluorimetry.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Organic (carbon based) solutions such anthracene or stilbene, dissolved in benzene or toluene, fluoresce with ultraviolet or gamma ray irradiation.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] The decay times of this fluorescence are on the order of nanoseconds, since the duration of the light depends on the lifetime of the excited states of the fluorescent material, in this case anthracene or stilbene.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Scintillation is defined a flash of light produced in a transparent material by the passage of a particle (an electron, an alpha particle, an ion, or a high-energy photon).
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Stilbene and derivatives are used in scintillation counters to detect such particles.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Stilbene is also one of the gain mediums used in dye lasers.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] Fluorescence is observed in the atmosphere when the air is under energetic electron bombardment.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] In cases such as the natural aurora, high-altitude nuclear explosions, and rocket-borne electron gun experiments, the molecules and ions formed have a fluorescent response to light.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] In August 2020 researchers reported the creation of the brightest fluorescent solid optical materials so far by enabling the transfer of properties of highly fluorescent dyes via spatial and electronic isolation of the dyes by mixing cationic dyes with anion-binding cyanostar macrocycles.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p01] According to a co-author these materials may have applications in areas such as solar energy harvesting, bioimaging, and lasers.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] The common fluorescent lamp relies on fluorescence.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Inside the glass tube is a partial vacuum and a small amount of mercury.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] An electric discharge in the tube causes the mercury atoms to emit mostly ultraviolet light.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] The tube is lined with a coating of a fluorescent material, called the *phosphor*, which absorbs ultraviolet light and re-emits visible light.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Fluorescent lighting is more energy-efficient than incandescent lighting elements.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] However, the uneven spectrum of traditional fluorescent lamps may cause certain colors to appear different from when illuminated by incandescent light or daylight.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] The mercury vapor emission spectrum is dominated by a short-wave UV line at 254 nm (which provides most of the energy to the phosphors), accompanied by visible light emission at 436 nm (blue), 546 nm (green) and 579 nm (yellow-orange).
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] These three lines can be observed superimposed on the white continuum using a hand spectroscope, for light emitted by the usual white fluorescent tubes.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Fluorescent lights were first available to the public at the 1939 New York World's Fair.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Improvements since then have largely been better phosphors, longer life, and more consistent internal discharge, and easier-to-use shapes (such as compact fluorescent lamps).
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Some high-intensity discharge (HID) lamps couple their even-greater electrical efficiency with phosphor enhancement for better color rendition.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] White light-emitting diodes (LEDs) became available in the mid-1990s as LED lamps, in which blue light emitted from the semiconductor strikes phosphors deposited on the tiny chip.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] The combination of the blue light that continues through the phosphor and the green to red fluorescence from the phosphors produces a net emission of white light.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Glow sticks sometimes utilize fluorescent materials to absorb light from the chemiluminescent reaction and emit light of a different color.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Many analytical procedures involve the use of a fluorometer, usually with a single exciting wavelength and single detection wavelength.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Because of the sensitivity that the method affords, fluorescent molecule concentrations as low as 1 part per trillion can be measured.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Fluorescence in several wavelengths can be detected by an array detector, to detect compounds from HPLC flow.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Also, TLC plates can be visualized if the compounds or a coloring reagent is fluorescent.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Fluorescence is most effective when there is a larger ratio of atoms at lower energy levels in a Boltzmann distribution.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] There is, then, a higher probability of excitement and release of photons by lower-energy atoms, making analysis more efficient.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Usually the setup of a fluorescence assay involves a light source, which may emit many different wavelengths of light.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] In general, a single wavelength is required for proper analysis, so, in order to selectively filter the light, it is passed through an excitation monochromator, and then that chosen wavelength is passed through the sample cell.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] After absorption and re-emission of the energy, many wavelengths may emerge due to Stokes shift and various electron transitions.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] To separate and analyze them, the fluorescent radiation is passed through an emission monochromator, and observed selectively by a detector.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Lasers most often use the fluorescence of certain materials as their active media, such as the red glow produced by a ruby (chromium sapphire), the infrared of titanium sapphire, or the unlimited range of colors produced by organic dyes.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] These materials normally fluoresce through a process called spontaneous emission, in which the light is emitted in all directions and often at many discrete spectral lines all at once.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] In many lasers, the fluorescent medium is "pumped" by exposing it to an intense light source, creating a population inversion, meaning that more of its atoms become in an excited state (high energy) rather than at ground state (low energy).
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] When this occurs, the spontaneous fluorescence can then induce the other atoms to emit their photons in the same direction and at the same wavelength, creating stimulated emission.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] When a portion of the spontaneous fluorescence is trapped between two mirrors, nearly all of the medium's fluorescence can be stimulated to emit along the same line, producing a laser beam.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] In fact, a protein or other component can be "labelled" with an extrinsic fluorophore, a fluorescent dye that can be a small molecule, protein, or quantum dot, finding a large use in many biological applications.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Fingerprints can be visualized with fluorescent compounds such as ninhydrin or DFO (1,8-Diazafluoren-9-one).
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Blood and other substances are sometimes detected by fluorescent reagents, like fluorescein.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Fibers, and other materials that may be encountered in forensics or with a relationship to various collectibles, are sometimes fluorescent.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Fluorescent penetrant inspection is used to find cracks and other defects on the surface of a part.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Dye tracing, using fluorescent dyes, is used to find leaks in liquid and gas plumbing systems.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Fluorescent colors are frequently used in signage, particularly road signs.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Fluorescent colors are generally recognizable at longer ranges than their non-fluorescent counterparts, with fluorescent orange being particularly noticeable.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] This property has led to its frequent use in safety signs and labels.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Fluorescent compounds are often used to enhance the appearance of fabric and paper, causing a "whitening" effect.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] A white surface treated with an optical brightener can emit more visible light than that which shines on it, making it appear brighter.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] The blue light emitted by the brightener compensates for the diminishing blue of the treated material and changes the hue away from yellow or brown and toward white.
[src:photochemistry/fluorescence-p02] Optical brighteners are used in laundry detergents, high brightness paper, cosmetics, high-visibility clothing and more.
[src:photochemistry/jablonski-diagram] In molecular spectroscopy, a **Jablonski diagram** is a diagram that illustrates the electronic states and often the vibrational levels of a molecule, and also the transitions between them.
[src:photochemistry/jablonski-diagram] The states are arranged vertically by energy and grouped horizontally by spin multiplicity.
[src:photochemistry/jablonski-diagram] Nonradiative transitions are indicated by squiggly arrows and radiative transitions by straight arrows.
[src:photochemistry/jablonski-diagram] The vibrational ground states of each electronic state are indicated with thick lines, the higher vibrational states with thinner lines.
[src:photochemistry/jablonski-diagram] The diagram is named after the Polish physicist Aleksander Jabłoński who first proposed it in 1933.
[src:photochemistry/jablonski-diagram] When a molecule absorbs a photon, the photon energy is converted and increases the molecule's internal energy level.
[src:photochemistry/jablonski-diagram] Likewise, when an excited molecule releases energy, it can do so in the form of a photon.
[src:photochemistry/jablonski-diagram] Depending on the energy of the photon, this could correspond to a change in vibrational, electronic, or rotational energy levels.
[src:photochemistry/jablonski-diagram] The changes between these levels are called "transitions" and are plotted on the Jablonski diagram.
[src:photochemistry/jablonski-diagram] Radiative transitions involve either the absorption or emission of a photon.
[src:photochemistry/jablonski-diagram] As mentioned above, these transitions are denoted with solid arrows with their tails at the initial energy level and their tips at the final energy level.
[src:photochemistry/jablonski-diagram] Nonradiative transitions arise through several different mechanisms, all differently labeled in the diagram.
[src:photochemistry/jablonski-diagram] Relaxation of the excited state to its lowest vibrational level is called vibrational relaxation (VR).
[src:photochemistry/jablonski-diagram] This process involves the dissipation of energy from the molecule to its surroundings, and thus it cannot occur for isolated molecules.
[src:photochemistry/jablonski-diagram] A second type of nonradiative transition is internal conversion (IC), which occurs when a vibrational state of an electronically excited state can couple to a vibrational state of a lower electronic state.
[src:photochemistry/jablonski-diagram] The molecule could then subsequently relax further through vibrational relaxation.
[src:photochemistry/jablonski-diagram] A third type is intersystem crossing (ISC); this is a transition to a state with a different spin multiplicity.
[src:photochemistry/jablonski-diagram] In molecules with large spin-orbit coupling, intersystem crossing is much more important than in molecules that exhibit only small spin-orbit coupling.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] In a general sense, there is no distinct boundary between the emission times of fluorescence and phosphorescence (i.e. if a substance glows under a black light it is generally considered fluorescent, and if it glows in the dark it is often simply called phosphorescent).
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] In a modern, scientific sense, the phenomena can usually be classified by the three different mechanisms that produce the light and the typical timescales at which they emit light: fluorescence, triplet phosphorescence, and persistent phosphorescence.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Whereas fluorescent materials stop emitting light within nanoseconds (billionths of a second) after the excitation radiation is removed, phosphorescent materials may continue to emit an afterglow ranging from a few microseconds to many hours after the excitation is removed.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Everyday examples of phosphorescent materials are the glow-in-the-dark toys, stickers, paint, and clock dials that glow after being charged with a bright light such as in any normal reading or room light.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Typically, the glow slowly fades out, sometimes within a few minutes or up to a few hours in a dark room.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] The study of phosphorescent materials led to the discovery of radioactive decay.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Uranium salts, a known phosphorescent material, fog x-ray sensitive photographic plates, but for years it was thought that phosphorescence was the sole cause of this.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] The salts were enclosed with a photographic plate in a drawer, and in one of physics' more accidental discoveries, the plates fogged despite the absence of an initial external stimulation by the sun.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] The result prompted a report by Henri Becquerel in 1898 to the Academy of Sciences.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] His claim that the uranium salts emitted radiation inspired the work of Marie Curie in following years, and yielded a Nobel Prize for both in 1903.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] The term *phosphorescence* comes from the Ancient Greek word *φῶς* (*phos*), meaning "light", and the Greek suffix *-φόρος* (*-phoros*), meaning "to bear", combined with the Latin suffix *-escentem*, meaning "becoming of", "having a tendency towards", or "with the essence of".
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Thus, phosphorescence literally means "having a tendency to bear light".
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] The term *phosphor* had been used since the Middle Ages to describe minerals that glowed in the dark.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] One of the most famous, but not the first, was Bolognian phosphor.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Around 1604, Vincenzo Casciarolo discovered a "lapis solaris" near Bologna, Italy.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Once heated in an oxygen-rich furnace, it thereafter absorbed sunlight and glowed in the dark.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] In 1677, Hennig Brand isolated a new element that glowed due to a chemiluminescent reaction when exposed to air, and named it "phosphorus".
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Stokes formed the term from a combination of fluorspar and opalescence (preferring to use a mineral instead of a solution), albeit it was later discovered that fluorspar glows due to phosphorescence.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] There was much confusion between the meanings of these terms throughout the late nineteenth to mid-twentieth centuries.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Only after the 1950s and 1960s did advances in quantum electronics, spectroscopy, and lasers provide a measure to distinguish between the various processes that emit the light, although in common speech the distinctions are still often rather vague.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] In simple terms, phosphorescence is a process in which energy absorbed by a substance is released relatively slowly in the form of light.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] This is in some cases the mechanism used for glow-in-the-dark materials which are "charged" by exposure to light.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Unlike the relatively swift reactions in fluorescence, such as those seen in laser mediums like the common ruby, phosphorescent materials "store" absorbed energy for a longer time, as the processes required to reemit energy occur less often.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] However, timescale is still only a general distinction, as there are slow-emitting fluorescent materials, for example uranyl salts, and, likewise, some phosphorescent materials like zinc sulfide (in violet) are very fast.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Scientifically, the phenomena are classified by the different mechanisms that produce the light, as materials that phosphoresce may be suitable for some purposes such as lighting, but may be completely unsuitable for others that require fluorescence, like lasers.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Further blurring the lines, a substance may emit light by one, two, or all three mechanisms depending on the material and excitation conditions.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] When the stored energy becomes locked in by the spin of the atomic electrons, a triplet state can occur, slowing the emission of light, sometimes by several orders of magnitude.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Conversely, when the stored energy is due to persistent phosphorescence, an entirely different process occurs without a fluorescence precursor.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] When electrons become trapped within a defect in the atomic or molecular lattice, light is prevented from reemitting until the electron can escape.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] To escape, the electron needs a boost of thermal energy to help spring it out of the trap and back into orbit around the atom.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Thus, persistent phosphorescence is highly dependent on the temperature of the material.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Most photoluminescent events, in which a chemical substrate absorbs and then re-emits a photon of light, are fast, in the order of 10 nanoseconds.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Light is absorbed and emitted at these fast time scales in cases where the energy of the photons involved matches the available energy states and allowed transitions of the substrate.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] In the special case of phosphorescence, the electron which absorbed the photon (energy) undergoes an unusual intersystem crossing into an energy state of different (usually higher) *spin multiplicity* (*see term symbol*), usually a triplet state.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] As a result, the excited electron can become trapped in the triplet state with only "forbidden" transitions available to return to the lower energy singlet state.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] These transitions, although "forbidden", will still occur in quantum mechanics but are kinetically unfavored and thus progress at significantly slower time scales.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Most phosphorescent compounds are still relatively fast emitters, with triplet decay-times in the order of milliseconds.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Common examples include the phosphor coatings used in fluorescent lamps, where phosphorescence on the order of milliseconds or longer is useful for filling in the "off-time" between alternating current cycles, helping to reduce "flicker".
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Even substances commonly associated with fluorescence may in fact be prone to phosphorescence, such as the liquid dyes found in highlighter pens, which is a common problem in liquid dye lasers.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] The onset of phosphorescence in this case can sometimes be reduced or delayed significantly by the use of triplet-quenching agents.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] $S_{0}+h\nu \to S_{1}\to T_{1}\to S_{0}+h\nu ^{\prime }\$ where S is a singlet and T a triplet whose subscripts denote states (0 is the ground state, and 1 the excited state).
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Transitions can also occur to higher energy levels, but the first excited state is denoted for simplicity.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Solid materials typically come in two main types: crystalline and amorphous.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] In either case, a lattice or network of atoms and molecules form.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] In crystals, the lattice is a very neat, uniform assembly.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] However, nearly all crystals have defects in the stacking sequence of these molecules and atoms.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] A vacancy defect, where an atom is simply missing from its place, leaving an empty "hole", is one type of defect.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Sometimes atoms can move from place to place within the lattice, creating Schottky defects or Frenkel defects.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Other defects can occur from impurities in the lattice.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] For example, when a normal atom is substituted by a different atom of much larger or smaller size, a substitutional defect occurs, while an interstitial defect occurs when a much smaller atom gets trapped in the "interstices", or the spaces between atoms.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] In contrast, amorphous materials have no "long-range order" (beyond the space of a few atoms in any direction), thus by definition are filled with defects.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] When a defect occurs, depending on the type and material, it can create a hole, or a "trap".
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] For example, a missing oxygen atom from a zinc oxide compound creates a hole in the lattice, surrounded by unbound zinc-atoms.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] This creates a net force or attraction that can be measured in electron-volts.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] When a high-energy photon strikes one of the zinc atoms, its electron absorbs the photon and is thrown out into a higher orbit.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] The electron may then enter the trap and be held in place (out of its normal orbit) by the attraction.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] To trigger the release of the energy, a random spike in thermal energy of sufficient magnitude is needed to boost the electron out of the trap and back into its normal orbit.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Once in orbit, the electron's energy can drop back to normal (ground state) resulting in the release of a photon.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] The release of energy in this way is a completely random process, governed mostly by the average temperature of the material versus the "depth" of the trap, or how many electron-volts it exerts.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] A trap that has a depth of 2.0 electron-volts would require a great amount of thermal energy (very high temperature) to overcome the attraction, while at a depth of 0.1 electron-volts very little heat (very cold temperature) is needed for the trap to even hold an electron.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Generally, higher temperatures cause a faster release of energy, resulting in a brighter yet short-lived emission, while lower temperatures produce a dimmer but longer-lasting glow.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Temperatures that are too hot or cold, depending on the substance, may not allow the accumulation or release of energy at all.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] The ideal depth of trap for persistent phosphorescence at room temperature is typically between 0.6 and 0.7 electron-volts.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] If the phosphorescent quantum yield is high, that is, if the substance has a large number of traps of the correct depth, this substance will release a significant amount of light over a long period of time, creating a so-called "glow in the dark" material.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Some examples of glow-in-the-dark materials do not glow by phosphorescence.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] For example, glow sticks glow due to a chemiluminescent process which is commonly mistaken for phosphorescence.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] In chemiluminescence, an excited state is created via a chemical reaction.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] The light emission tracks the kinetic progress of the underlying chemical reaction.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] The excited state will then transfer to a dye molecule, also known as a sensitizer or fluorophor, and subsequently fluoresce back to the ground state.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Common pigments used in phosphorescent materials include zinc sulfide and strontium aluminate.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Use of zinc sulfide for safety-related products dates back to the 1930s.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] The development of strontium aluminate pigments in 1993 was spurred on by the need to find a substitute for glow-in-the-dark materials with high luminance and long phosphorescence, especially those that used promethium.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] This led to the discovery by Yasumitsu Aoki (Nemoto & Co.) of materials with luminance approximately 10 times greater than zinc sulfide and phosphorescence approximately 10 times longer.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] This has relegated most zinc sulfide based products to the novelty category.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Strontium aluminate-based pigments are now used in exit signs, pathway marking, and other safety-related signage.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] One strategy to enhance the ISC and phosphorescence is the incorporation of heavy atoms, which increase spin-orbit coupling (SOC).
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Additionally, the SOC (and therefore the ISC) can be promoted by coupling n-π* and π-π* transitions with different angular momenta, also known as Mostafa El-Sayed's rule.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Such transitions are typically exhibited by carbonyl or triazine derivatives, and most organic room-temperature phosphorescent (ORTP) materials incorporate such moieties.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] In 1974 Becky Schroeder was given a US patent for her invention of the "Glow Sheet" which used phosphorescent lines under writing paper to help people write in low-light conditions.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Glow in the dark material is added to the plastic blend used in injection molds to make some disc golf discs, which allow the game to be played at night.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Often clock faces of watches are painted with phosphorescent colours.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Therefore, they can be used in absolute dark environments for several hours after having been exposed to bright light.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] A common use of phosphorescence is decoration.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Stars made of glow-in-the-dark plastic are placed on walls, ceilings, or hanging from strings make a room look like the night sky.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Other objects like figurines, cups, posters, lamp fixtures, toys and bracelet beads may also glow.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Using blacklights makes these things glow brightly, common at raves, bedrooms, theme parks, and festivals.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] A shadow wall is created when a light flashes upon a person or object in front of a phosphorescent screen which temporarily captures the shadow.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] The screen or wall is painted with a glow-in-the-dark product that contains phosphorescent compounds.
[src:photochemistry/phosphorescence] Publicly, these shadow walls can be found at certain science museums.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] In nature, photochemistry is of immense importance as it is the basis of photosynthesis, vision, and the formation of vitamin D with sunlight.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] It is also responsible for the appearance of DNA mutations leading to skin cancers.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Photochemical reactions proceed differently than temperature-driven reactions.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Photochemical paths access high-energy intermediates that cannot be generated thermally, thereby overcoming large activation barriers in a short period of time, and allowing reactions otherwise inaccessible by thermal processes.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Photochemistry can also be destructive, as illustrated by the photodegradation of plastics.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Photoexcitation is the first step in a photochemical process: the reactant is elevated to a state of higher energy, an excited state.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] The first law of photochemistry, known as the Grotthuss–Draper law (for chemists Theodor Grotthuss and John W.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Draper), states that light must be absorbed by a chemical substance in order for a photochemical reaction to take place.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] According to the second law of photochemistry, known as the Stark–Einstein law (for physicists Johannes Stark and Albert Einstein), for each photon of light absorbed by a chemical system, no more than one molecule is activated for a photochemical reaction, as defined by the quantum yield.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] When a substance in its ground state (S0) absorbs light, one electron is excited.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] According to the spin selection rule; other transitions would violate the law of conservation of angular momentum.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] The excitation to a higher singlet state can be from HOMO to LUMO or to a higher orbital, so that singlet excitation states S1, S2, S3... at different energies are possible.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Kasha's rule stipulates that higher singlet states quickly relax by radiationless decay or internal conversion (IC) to S1.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Thus, S1 is usually, but not always, the only relevant singlet excited state.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] This excited state S1 can further relax to S0 by IC, but also by an allowed radiative transition from S1 to S0 that emits a photon; this process is called fluorescence.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Alternatively, it is possible for the excited state S1 to undergo spin inversion and to generate a triplet excited state T1 having two unpaired electrons with the same spin.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] This violation of the spin selection rule is possible by intersystem crossing (ISC) of the vibrational and electronic levels of S1 and T1.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] According to Hund's rule of maximum multiplicity, this T1 state would be somewhat more stable than S1.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] This triplet state can relax to the ground state S0 by radiationless ISC or by a radiation pathway called phosphorescence.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] This process implies a change of electronic spin, which is forbidden by spin selection rules, making phosphorescence (from T1 to S0) much slower than fluorescence (from S1 to S0).
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Thus, triplet states generally have longer lifetimes than singlet states.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] These transitions are usually summarized in a state energy diagram or Jablonski diagram, the paradigm of molecular photochemistry.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] These excited species, either S1 or T1, have a half-empty low-energy orbital, and are consequently more oxidizing than the ground state.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] But at the same time, they have an electron in a high-energy orbital, and are thus more reducing.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] In general, excited species are prone to participate in electron transfer processes.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Photochemical reactions require a light source that emits wavelengths corresponding to an electronic transition in the reactant.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] In the early experiments (and in everyday life), sunlight was the light source, although it is polychromatic.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Mercury-vapor lamps are more common in the laboratory.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Low-pressure mercury-vapor lamps mainly emit at 254 nm.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] For polychromatic sources, wavelength ranges can be selected using filters.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Alternatively, laser beams are usually monochromatic (although two or more wavelengths can be obtained using nonlinear optics), and LEDs have a relatively narrow band that can be efficiently used, as well as Rayonet lamps, to get approximately monochromatic beams.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] The emitted light must reach the targeted functional group without being blocked by the reactor, medium, or other functional groups present.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] For many applications, quartz is used for the reactors as well as to contain the lamp.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Pyrex absorbs at wavelengths shorter than 275 nm.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] The solvent is an important experimental parameter.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Solvents are potential reactants, and for this reason, chlorinated solvents are avoided because the C–Cl bond can lead to chlorination of the substrate.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Strongly-absorbing solvents prevent photons from reaching the substrate.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Hydrocarbon solvents absorb only at short wavelengths and are thus preferred for photochemical experiments requiring high-energy photons.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Solvents containing unsaturation absorb at longer wavelengths and can usefully filter out short wavelengths.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] For example, cyclohexane and acetone "cut off" (absorb strongly) at wavelengths shorter than 215 and 330 nm, respectively.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Typically, the wavelength employed to induce a photochemical process is selected based on the absorption spectrum of the reactive species, most often the absorption maximum.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Over the last years, however, it has been demonstrated that, in the majority of bond-forming reactions, the absorption spectrum does not allow selecting the optimum wavelength to achieve the highest reaction yield based on absorptivity.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] This fundamental mismatch between absorptivity and reactivity has been elucidated with so-called photochemical action plots.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Continuous-flow photochemistry offers multiple advantages over batch photochemistry.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Photochemical reactions are driven by the number of photons that are able to activate molecules causing the desired reaction.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] The large surface-area-to-volume ratio of a microreactor maximizes the illumination, and at the same time allows for efficient cooling, which decreases the thermal side products.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Examples of photochemical organic reactions are electrocyclic reactions, radical reactions, photoisomerization, and Norrish reactions.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Alkenes undergo many important reactions that proceed via a photon-induced π to π* transition.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] The first electronic excited state of an alkene lacks the π-bond, so that rotation about the C–C bond is rapid and the molecule engages in reactions not observed thermally.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] These reactions include cis-trans isomerization and cycloaddition to other (ground state) alkene to give cyclobutane derivatives.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] The cis-trans isomerization of a (poly)alkene is involved in retinal, a component of the machinery of vision.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] The dimerization of alkenes is relevant to the photodamage of DNA, where thymine dimers are observed upon illuminating DNA with UV radiation.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Such dimers interfere with transcription.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] The beneficial effects of sunlight are associated with the photochemically-induced retro-cyclization (decyclization) reaction of ergosterol to give vitamin D.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] In the DeMayo reaction, an alkene reacts with a 1,3-diketone reacts via its enol to yield a 1,5-diketone.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Still another common photochemical reaction is Howard Zimmerman's di-π-methane rearrangement.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] In an industrial application, about 100,000 tonnes of benzyl chloride are prepared annually by the gas-phase photochemical reaction of toluene with chlorine.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] The light is absorbed by chlorine molecules, the low energy of this transition being indicated by the yellowish color of the gas.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Mercaptans can be produced by photochemical addition of hydrogen sulfide (H2S) to alpha olefins.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Coordination complexes and organometallic compounds are also photoreactive.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] These reactions can entail cis-trans isomerization.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] More commonly, photoreactions result in dissociation of ligands, since the photon excites an electron on the metal to an orbital that is antibonding with respect to the ligands.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Thus, metal carbonyls that resist thermal substitution undergo decarbonylation upon irradiation with UV light.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Select photoreactive coordination complexes can undergo oxidation-reduction processes via single electron transfer.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] This electron transfer can occur within the inner or outer coordination sphere of the metal.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] The efficiency of a photochemical reaction can be expressed by the quantum yield (Φ).
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] Although bleaching has long been practiced, the first photochemical reaction was described by Trommsdorff in 1834.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] He observed that crystals of the compound α-santonin when exposed to sunlight turned yellow and burst.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] In a 2007 study the reaction was described as a succession of three steps taking place within a single crystal.
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] The first step is a rearrangement reaction to a cyclopentadienone intermediate (**2**), the second one a dimerization in a Diels–Alder reaction (**3**), and the third one an intramolecular [2+2]cycloaddition (**4**).
[src:photochemistry/photochemistry] The bursting effect is attributed to a large change in crystal volume on dimerization.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] In chemistry, **photoisomerization** is a form of isomerization induced by photoexcitation.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] Both reversible and irreversible photoisomerizations are known for photoswitchable compounds.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] The term "photoisomerization" usually, however, refers to a reversible process.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] Photoisomerization of the compound retinal in the eye allows for vision.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] Photoisomerizable substrates have been put to practical use, for instance, in pigments for rewritable CDs, DVDs, and 3D optical data storage solutions.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] In addition, interest in photoisomerizable molecules has been aimed at molecular devices, such as molecular switches, molecular motors, and molecular electronics.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] Another class of device that uses the photoisomerization process is as an additive in liquid crystals to change their linear and nonlinear properties.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] Due to the photoisomerization is possible to induce a molecular reorientation in the liquid crystal bulk, which is used in holography, as spatial filter or optical switching.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] Azobenzenes, stilbenes, spiropyrans, are prominent classes of compounds subject to photoisomerism.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] In the presence of a catalyst, norbornadiene converts to quadricyclane via ~300nm UV radiation.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] When converted back to norbornadiene, quadryicyclane’s ring strain energy is liberated in the form of heat (*ΔH* = −89 kJ/mol).
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] This reaction has been proposed to store solar energy (photoswitchs).
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] Photoisomerization behavior can be roughly categorized into several classes.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] Two major classes are *trans*–*cis* (or *E*–*Z*) conversion, and open-closed ring transition.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] Examples of the former include stilbene and azobenzene.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] This type of compounds has a double bond, and rotation or inversion around the double bond affords isomerization between the two states.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] Examples of the latter include fulgide and diarylethene.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] This type of compounds undergoes bond cleavage and bond creation upon irradiation with particular wavelengths of light.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] Still another class is the di-π-methane rearrangement.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] Many complexes are often photosensitive and many of these complexes undergo photoisomerization.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] One case is the conversion of the colorless cis-bis(triphenylphosphine)platinum chloride to the yellow trans isomer.
[src:photochemistry/photoisomerization] Some coordination complexes undergo change in their spin state upon illumination, i.e. these are photosensitive spin crossover complexes.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] In particle physics, the **quantum yield** (denoted Φ) of a radiation-induced process is the number of times a specific event occurs per photon absorbed by the system.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] The fluorescence quantum yield (FQY) is defined as the ratio of the number of photons emitted to the number of photons absorbed.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] Fluorescence quantum yield is measured on a scale from 0 to 1.0, but is often represented as a percentage.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] A quantum yield of 1.0 (100%) describes a process where each photon absorbed results in a photon emitted.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] Substances with the largest quantum yields, such as rhodamines, display the brightest emissions; however, compounds with quantum yields of 0.10 are still considered quite fluorescent.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] Non-radiative processes are excited state decay mechanisms other than photon emission, which include: Förster resonance energy transfer, internal conversion, external conversion, and intersystem crossing.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] Thus, the fluorescence quantum yield is affected if the rate of any non-radiative pathway changes.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] The quantum yield can be close to unity if the non-radiative decay rate is much smaller than the rate of radiative decay, that is *kf* > *k*nr.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] Fluorescence quantum yields are measured by comparison to a standard of known quantum yield.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] The quinine in 0.1M perchloric acid (Φ = 0.60) shows no temperature dependence up to 45 °C, therefore it can be considered as a reliable standard solution.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] Experimentally, relative fluorescence quantum yields can be determined by measuring fluorescence of a fluorophore of known quantum yield with the same experimental parameters (excitation wavelength, slit widths, photomultiplier voltage etc.) as the substance in question.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] The subscript R denotes the respective values of the reference substance.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] The determination of fluorescence quantum yields in scattering media requires additional considerations and corrections.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] A fluorophore's environment can impact quantum yield, usually resulting from changes in the rates of non-radiative decay.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] Many fluorophores used to label macromolecules are sensitive to solvent polarity.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] The class of 8-anilinonaphthalene-1-sulfonic acid (ANS) probe molecules are essentially non-fluorescent when in aqueous solution, but become highly fluorescent in nonpolar solvents or when bound to proteins and membranes.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] The quantum yield of ANS is ~0.002 in aqueous buffer, but near 0.4 when bound to serum albumin.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] In a chemical photodegradation process, when a molecule dissociates after absorbing a light quantum, the quantum yield is the number of destroyed molecules divided by the number of photons absorbed by the system.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] Since not all photons are absorbed productively, the typical quantum yield will be less than 1.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] Quantum yields greater than 1 are possible for photo-induced or radiation-induced chain reactions, in which a single photon may trigger a long chain of transformations.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] One example is the reaction of hydrogen with chlorine, in which as many as 106 molecules of hydrogen chloride can be formed per quantum of blue light absorbed.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] Quantum yields of photochemical reactions can be highly dependent on the structure, proximity and concentration of the reactive chromophores, the type of solvent environment as well as the wavelength of the incident light.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] Such effects can be studied with wavelength-tunable lasers and the resulting quantum yield data can help predict conversion and selectivity of photochemical reactions.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] In optical spectroscopy, the quantum yield is the probability that a given quantum state is formed from the system initially prepared in some other quantum state.
[src:photochemistry/quantum-yield] For example, a singlet to triplet transition quantum yield is the fraction of molecules that, after being photoexcited into a singlet state, cross over to the triplet state.
